[[File:Teli Ka Mandir, Gwalior Fort.JPG|thumb|244px|Front view of the Teli Ka Mandir, Gwalior Fort]]

'''Teli ka Mandir''' is a [[Hindu temple]] located within the [[Gwalior Fort]] in [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[India]]. Dedicated to the god [[Vishnu]], it has been dated to between the 8th and 11th centuries AD.<ref name="Allen1991">{{cite book|author=Margaret Prosser Allen|title=Ornament in Indian Architecture|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=vyXxEX5PQH8C&pg=RA1-PA203|date=1 January 1991|publisher=University of Delaware Press|isbn=978-0-87413-399-8|pages=1<U+2013>}}</ref> It is both the loftiest and oldest surviving structure within the fort.<ref>{{cite book|title=India. Ediz. Inglese|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=vK88ktao7pIC&pg=PA674|year=2009|publisher=Lonely Planet|isbn=978-1-74220-347-8|pages=674<U+2013>}}</ref>

== Etymology ==
Probably meaning the ''Oilman's Temple'', the etymology of the temple's name has several contending theories.<ref name="BettsMcCulloch2013">{{cite book|author1=Vanessa Betts|author2=Victoria McCulloch|title=Delhi to Kolkata Footprint Focus Guide|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=acT9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA85|date=30 October 2013|publisher=Footprint Travel Guides|isbn=978-1-909268-40-1|pages=85<U+2013>}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Fortifying legends|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/todays-paper/tp-life/fortifying-legends/article1115099.ece|accessdate=11 December 2014|publisher=The Hindu Businessline|date=9 May 2008}}</ref> One theory holds that the temple was built by members of the [[Teli|Teli community]] of oil merchants during the reign of the Pratihara king [[Mihira Bhoja I|Mihirabhoja]] during the 8th or 9th century AD.<ref name="Publications">{{cite book|author=Goodearth Publications|title=Temples of Madhya Pradesh|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=THW_OkoTuE4C&pg=PA46|publisher=Goodearth Publications|isbn=978-93-80262-49-9|pages=46<U+2013>}}</ref> It is also thought to have derived its name from the Telang [[Brahmins]] who were charged with presiding over all religious ceremonies after the fort was captured by a [[Rashtrakuta dynasty|Rashtrakuta]] king in the 8th century.<ref name="Publications">{{cite book|author=Goodearth Publications|title=Temples of Madhya Pradesh|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=THW_OkoTuE4C&pg=PA46|publisher=Goodearth Publications|isbn=978-93-80262-49-9|pages=46<U+2013>}}</ref> Another theory holds that it has been named after the [[Telangana region]] of [[southern India]] owing to its evident Dravidian influence.<ref name="Sen2011">{{cite book|author=Probir Sen|title=Madhya Pradesh: Unhurried, Unspoilt, Undiscovered|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=j7zsVCQi25kC&pg=PT14|date=1 June 2011|publisher=SCB Distributors|isbn=978-81-8328-220-8|pages=14<U+2013>}}</ref><ref name="Pal2014">{{cite book|author=Susant Pal|title=Imbibed In Faith|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=n-3HAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA228|date=January 2014|publisher=Partridge Publishing (Authorsolutions)|isbn=978-1-4828-1258-9|pages=228<U+2013>}}</ref> 

== History ==
[[File:Temple in Gwalior Fort.jpg|thumb|244px|Teli Ka Mandir, circa 1881]]
Teli ka Mandir is thought to have been built circa 850 AD during the reign of the [[Pratiharas|Pratihara king]] Mihira Bhoja.<ref name="Bajpai2006">{{cite book|author=K. D. Bajpai|title=History of Gop<U+0101>chala|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Q3KcwLKuRnYC&pg=PA31|year=2006|publisher=Bharatiya Jnanpith|isbn=978-81-263-1155-2|pages=31<U+2013>}}</ref> Following the [[Revolt of 1857]], the British used the temple as a soda factory.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Rough Guide to India|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=kAMik_6LbwUC&pg=PA406|year=2003|publisher=Rough Guides|isbn=978-1-84353-089-3|pages=406<U+2013>}}</ref> Between 1881 - 1883, repairs to the temple were initiated by Major Keith, an officer of the [[Royal Scots Regiment]] stationed in Gwalior.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Panoramic past|journal=Frontline|date=17 May 2013|url=http://www.frontline.in/books/panoramic-past/article4647706.ece|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref><ref name="MonumentsCole1882">{{cite book|author1=India. Curator of Ancient Monuments|author2=Henry Hardy Cole|title=Report of the Curator of Ancient Monuments in India for the Year ...|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=gnEIAAAAQAAJ&pg=PR17|year=1882|publisher=Government Central Branch Press|pages=17<U+2013>}}</ref>

== Architecture ==
Teli ka Mandir combines in it the [[Nagara architecture|Nagara]] and [[Dr<U+0101>vi<U+1E0D>a Style|Dravida]] styles of architecture and also shows influences of [[Buddhist architecture]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Gorgeous Gwalior|url=http://freepressjournal.in/gorgeous-gwalior/|accessdate=11 December 2014|publisher=Free Press Journal|date=16 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Teli-ka-Mandir and Suraj Kund|url=http://www.roughguides.com/destinations/asia/india/madhya-pradesh-chhattisgarh/gwalior/the-teli-ka-mandir-and-suraj-kund/|publisher=Rough Guides|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> The temple has a rectangular plan and is mounted by a barrel vault with the walls containing empty niches surmounted by tall pediments.<ref name="Inc.2009">{{cite book|author=Encyclopaedia Britannica, Inc.|title=Britannica Guide to India|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=BbqbAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA252|date=1 March 2009|publisher=Encyclopaedia Britannica, Inc.|isbn=978-1-59339-847-7|pages=252<U+2013>}}</ref><ref name="Kuiper2010">{{cite book|author=Kathleen Kuiper|title=The Culture of India|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=c8PJFLeURhsC&pg=PA307|date=15 August 2010|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-61530-149-2|pages=307<U+2013>}}</ref> The oblong, vaulted roof derives from the influence of Buddhist [[chaitya |chaitya architecture]] and bears resemblance to the [[Vaital Deula|Vaital Deul]] in [[Bhubaneshwar]].<ref name="BettsMcCulloch2013">{{cite book|author1=Vanessa Betts|author2=Victoria McCulloch|title=Delhi to Kolkata Footprint Focus Guide|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=acT9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA85|date=30 October 2013|publisher=Footprint Travel Guides|isbn=978-1-909268-40-1|pages=85<U+2013>}}</ref>

The temple is approached through a flight of stairs leading to a banded doorway containing sculptures of river goddesses and attendants in its lower part.<ref name="Sharma">{{cite book|author=Dr. Shiv Sharma|title=India - A Travel Guide|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=COHI7LlpkSAC&pg=PA531|publisher=Diamond Pocket Books (P) Ltd.|isbn=978-81-284-0067-4|pages=531<U+2013>}}</ref> There are [[Shaiva]] and [[Shakta]] [[Dvarapala|dvarapalas]] along the outer and inner doorways and the laters presence is thought to indicate the temple's dedication to the godess [[Shakti]].<ref name="Bajpai2006">{{cite book|author=K. D. Bajpai|title=History of Gop<U+0101>chala|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Q3KcwLKuRnYC&pg=PA31|year=2006|publisher=Bharatiya Jnanpith|isbn=978-81-263-1155-2|pages=31<U+2013>}}</ref> The doorway leads to the [[sanctum sanctorum]] or [[garbha griha]]. The [[mandapa]] is absent in the Teli ka Mandir.<ref name="Publications">{{cite book|author=Goodearth Publications|title=Temples of Madhya Pradesh|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=THW_OkoTuE4C&pg=PA46|publisher=Goodearth Publications|isbn=978-93-80262-49-9|pages=46<U+2013>}}</ref> There is a decorative sculpture of [[Garuda]] at the entrance to the temple.<ref name="Krishna1990">{{cite book|author=Brajesh Krishna|title=The art under the Gurjara-Pratih<U+0101>ras|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=PMmfAAAAMAAJ|date=1 January 1990|publisher=Harman Pub. House|isbn=978-81-85151-16-8}}</ref><ref name="BettsMcCulloch2013">{{cite book|author1=Vanessa Betts|author2=Victoria McCulloch|title=Delhi to Kolkata Footprint Focus Guide|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=acT9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA85|date=30 October 2013|publisher=Footprint Travel Guides|isbn=978-1-909268-40-1|pages=85<U+2013>}}</ref> The temple, 35 metres in height, is the loftiest building in the Gwalior Fort.<ref name="Dobbie2004">{{cite book|author=Aline Dobbie|title=India: The Tiger's Roar|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=-184ul4SfCAC&pg=PA61|year=2004|publisher=Melrose Press|isbn=978-0-9548480-2-6|pages=61<U+2013>}}</ref>

The temple has been dedicated to the Pratihara Vishnu.<ref>{{cite news|title=Adding a touch of royalty|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2001/07/09/stories/10097209.htm|accessdate=11 December 2014|publisher=The Hindu Businessline|date=9 July 2001}}</ref> [[James Fergusson (architect)|James Fergusson]] has opined that the Teli ka Mandir while originally a Vishnu temple was later converted into a Shiva temple.<ref name="Fergusson1876">{{cite book|author=James Fergusson|title=A history of architecture in all countries: from the earliest times to the present day. By James Fergusson|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=S2kOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA452|year=1876|publisher=John Murray|pages=452<U+2013>}}</ref>
The temple's [[Valabhi]] [[shikhara]] mirrors the [[gopuram]] of Dravidian temples and it stands on a Nagara base.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gwalior Fort|url=http://asi.nic.in/asi_monu_tktd_mp_gwalior.asp|publisher=Archaeological Survey of India|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> The temple's outer walls have been extensively carved and contain several excellent sculptures of [[Hindu gods and goddesses]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Gorgeous Gwalior|url=http://freepressjournal.in/gorgeous-gwalior/|accessdate=11 December 2014|publisher=Free Press Journal|date=16 November 2014}}</ref> 

